#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Square
{
public:
    int operator()(int x)
    {
        return x * x;
    }
};

int main()
{
    Square ob;

    cout << ob(4);

    return 0;
}

ob(4);

Compiler converts it to:

ob.operator()(4);

operator() overloads the function call operator.

It allows an object to behave like a function.

Objects overloading operator() are called Function Objects (Functors).

=========================================
FUNCTION CALL OPERATOR () INTERVIEW Q&A
=========================================

Q. What is operator()?
A. It overloads the function call operator so that an object
can be called like a function.

Q. What are objects overloading operator() called?
A. Function Objects (Functors).

Q. What does the compiler convert this into?

calc(10,20);

↓

calc.operator()(10,20);

Q. Why use Functors instead of normal functions?

- Can store state.****************
- Can be passed to STL algorithms.
- Can be inlined by the compiler.

Q. Where is operator() used?

- STL Algorithms
- Custom Comparators
- Lambda expressions (internally use function objects)
